column1: #Text=Wikinews interviews Spanish Paralympic swimmer Deborah Font
#Text=Deborah Font at Madrid – Barajas Airport on Friday Image : Laura Hale .
#Text=Wikinews interviews Deborah Font Audio : Laura Hale .

#Text=Last Friday at Madrid – Barajas Airport , Wikinews interviewed Spanish Paralympic swimmer Deborah Font , who is competing at the 2013 IPC Swimming World Championships that started this Monday in Montreal , Canada .

#Text=Font has finished second in Monday 's Women 's 100 meter Freestyle S12 Heat 1 , before going on to finish fourth in the Women 's 100 meter Freestyle S12 Final with a time of 1:03.20 , less than a second behind bronze medalist German Naomi Maike Schnittger .
#Text=I 'm Laura Hale , I 'm interviewing Deborah Font for Wikinews .
#Text=Deborah is going to the 2013 IPC Swimming World Championships in Montreal .
#Text=You 're already a Paralympic medallist , right ? You 've won several medals at the Paralympics before ?

#Text=: I won two medals in Sydney [ 2000 Summer Paralympic Games ] , a gold medal and bronze medal ; in Athens [ 2004 Summer Paralympic Games ] two silver medals and one bronze medal ; in Beijing [ 2008 Summer Paralympic Games ] one bronze medal ; and in London [ 2012 Summer Paralympic Games ] one bronze medal .
#Text=: I do n't know the exact number .
#Text=Okay , and you 're going to do that in Montreal ?
#Text=You think you 're going to get a medal ?
#Text=: Yes , I 'm fighting for a silver or bronze medal .
#Text=: Yeah , partial . [ I can see a little . ]
#Text=Since you cannot see perfectly , when you swim , can you see the people next to you ?
#Text=: I can see those next to me , but not perfectly .
#Text=I see those near to me , but not those far from me .
#Text=Do you think about other swimmers when you swim , or is it a disadvantage because you cannot see swimmers farther away ?
#Text=: I swim my race , and do n't see the other swimmers .
#Text=They do n't matter when you swim ?
#Text=You swim against yourself , your best time ?
#Text=: I swim against myself , I do n't see the other swimmers too much .
#Text=My race , myself , I go inside myself .
#Text=How difficult is it to swim in Spain for Paralympic swimmers when you do n't have sponsors ?
#Text=For the Olympics , athletes do n't have many sponsors , and for Paralympics it 's more difficult .
#Text=Is swimming more competitive in Barcelona , in Madrid ... ?
#Text=Where do you think the best swimmers come from ?
#Text=: They come from all Spain , but train only in Madrid or Barcelona .
#Text=Is there a reason most of the swimmers train in Barcelona ?
#Text=: There are more possibilities for training in good swimming pools .
#Text=The " Centros de Alto Rendimiento " [ High Performance Centres ] are in Madrid or Barcelona .
#Text=Coming in into the World Championships , did you do any special training , or change how you prepare ?

#Text=: I did special training with a coach that only trains three or four of us at the High Performance Centre . ( ( es))Spanish language : ‍Entrenamos con entrenador especial que por ejemplo él solo nos entrena a tres o cuatro paralímpicos , en el Centro de Alto Rendimiento pero con un entrenador especial que nos sigue a diario y que nos lo hace especialmente para nosotros .
#Text=This is a pretty dumb question , but I know a lot of people who look at blind swimmers and they go how can they swim at a straight line ?
#Text=Can you clarify how people with vision impairments can actually swim ?
#Text=: Well , in swimming it 's all technique and a lot of learning , and learning to swim by the middle of the lane involves a lot of training , habit ...
#Text=Perhaps it 's more difficult for completely blind people , but it 's all a matter of training , trying again and again , get to know the swimming pool ...

#Text=But I think the most difficult thing is to learn to swim the technique without being able to see the others , and to know what you are moving , your arm here and not there ... and learning to touch the wall , it 's harder to calculate , especially when competing , because you cannot see the distance you have to the wall . ( ( es))Spanish language : ‍Bueno , para nadar casi todo es técnica y mucho aprendizaje , y para nadar recto en la calle es por entrenamiento , por costumbre , por ... quizás es más dicifil cuando se es ciego total ir por el medio justo , pero bueno todo está entrenado , es a base de entrenar , intentarlo , conocerte la piscina ...

#Text=Pero creo que lo más dificil es aprender a nadar la técnica sin ver a los demás , y saber lo que estás moviendo , el brazo , y si lo pones aquí , no lo pones aquí , pues eso sí , y llegar a la pared también , es como más dificil de calcular , sobre todo en competición , que no ves la pared a la distancia que estás .
